   An appeals court in Illinois has ruled that in-house
lawyers can sue companies that have fired them in retaliation
for giving unwanted advice.
   The ruling, by the Appellate Court of Illinois, is
believed to be among the first to give staff lawyers the
right to sue employers for retaliatory discharge. The case
had been closely watched by in-house lawyers and legal ethics
experts because courts in Illinois and Texas had ruled that
in-house lawyers could not sue employers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The case involves Roger J. Balla, an in-house lawyer fired
in 1985 by Gambro Inc., a distributor of kidney dialysis
equipment. Before he was fired, Mr. Balla had told the
company that a shipment of dialyzers was "misbranded and/or
adulterated," according to the court opinion.
   A lower court ruled that Mr. Balla could not pursue his
retaliatory discharge claim against Gambro, now based in
Lakewood, Colo., its German parent and Swedish affiliate. But
the appeals court said that Mr. Balla could pursue his claim,
even though other courts had refused to allow in-house
attorneys to sue on such grounds "fearing that the attorneys
would breach their fiduciary duty by disclosing their
client's confidential information."
   "The sanctity of the attorney-client privilege is not an
absolute bar to disclosure," the court ruled, when "public
policies" or "serious bodily harm" are at stake.
   Mr. Balla's suit against Gambro will be heard by a lower
court.
   Arthur Sternberg, the Chicago lawyer who represents
Gambro, said his client will seek to appeal. He said the
decision makes in-house lawyers "second-class citizens"
because it will encourage companies to limit their "use of
in-house attorneys to more mundane types of tasks rather than
putting them in sensitive situations." He said the dialyzers
were "not defective in any way."
   Alan O. Amos, the Chicago lawyer for Mr. Balla, said the
decision shows that in-house lawyers have "the same rights
that any other employee would have under the same
circumstances." He said the decision will discourage
companies from hiding behind the attorney-client privilege.
   The American Corporate Counsel Association (ACCA), a trade
group, has taken the position that in-house lawyers should
not be able to sue their employers, according to board member
Lawrence A. Salibra. But ACCA will consider the issue again
at its annual meeting in November, said Mr. Salibra, senior
counsel at Alcan Aluminium Corp.
