   SEC DROPS BID for spot on Drexel creditors' committee.
   Instead, the Securities and Exchange Commission has
aligned itself with a court-sanctioned group of
securities-litigation claimants suing Drexel Burnham Lambert
Group Inc.
   The SEC moved to join the creditors' committee soon after
Drexel filed for bankruptcy-law protection on Feb. 13. The
SEC is owed $150 million as part of Drexel's settlement of
charges against the company last year. Although that claim
makes the SEC one of Drexel's largest creditors, the motion
sparked controversy because of a dispute over whether
bankruptcy law allowed a regulatory agency to serve in that
role.
   Now, however, the SEC says its interests are better
represented through the newly formed securities litigation
claimants group. The group will negotiate with Drexel and the
creditors' committee over how to provide for litigation
claims in the company's bankruptcy reorganization plan. More
than 400 suits are pending against Drexel.
   The group includes the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.,
which is expected to file a huge claim against Drexel
stemming from the failure of several savings and loans. The
group also represents investors who have filed class-action
suits against Drexel and Michael Milken, the company's former
junk-bond chief. The group, which isn't an official
bankruptcy committee, was approved in a court order by U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Howard Buschman III last month.
   Richard Kirby, the SEC's senior litigation counsel, said
the agency joined the litigation group because of the
importance of addressing the eventual claims that Drexel will
have to pay. The SEC's $150 million claim is meant to be
distributed to investors who were hurt by alleged wrongdoing
by Drexel. In a reorganization plan for Drexel, the money
could be combined with other payments by Drexel to set up a
fund for litigation claimants.
   "This case can't progress toward a feasible reorganization
plan" until an estimate is reached on the litigation claims,
Mr. Kirby said.
   In court filings, Drexel and the creditors' committee
agreed to negotiate with the litigation group to develop a
process for estimating the claims. They also said they will
include the group in negotiating a reorganization proposal.
