   CRAVATH HAS LOST General Development Corp. as a client.
   Cravath Swaine &amp; Moore, a New York law firm, and the
troubled Miami real-estate developer said the parting of ways
was mutual and had been planned since the spring. In the 13
months ended April 30, the company paid Cravath $4.8 million,
the law firm said.
   General Development was indicted in March on federal
felony charges of defrauding thousands of home buyers and was
subsequently placed in Chapter 11 bankruptcy-law proceedings.
Some critics, including Miami Beach attorney Paul Steinberg,
who represents certain General Development shareholders,
assert that Cravath ought to be held liable for advising
General Development that its marketing practices were legal
and sound.
   Meanwhile, two General Development directors said they
will call for an independent review of Cravath's legal
representation to assess whether the law firm acted
responsibly. The directors -- Chairman Charles J. Simons and
Chesterfield Smith -- said they are not alleging impropriety,
but rather feel an independent investigation is a sound
fiduciary move in light of criticism of Cravath.
   Ronald Rolfe, a Cravath partner, said "We think Cravath
has no liability or potential liability at all." Paul Dodyk,
who was Cravath's lead counsel for the company, declined to
comment.
   Mr. Smith, whose Miami law firm, Holland &amp; Knight, is
slated to succeed Cravath as lead counsel, said "it is in the
interest of all concerned to ascertain if the allegations are
substantial or insubstantial." The company's board hasn't yet
formally considered an independent inquiry, which would
review the roles of all involved parties -- not just Cravath,
Mr. Simons said.
   General Development had a close relationship with Cravath;
its former chairman, David F. Brown, who is facing federal
fraud charges, was a former associate at the firm and then
became general counsel to City Investing, a Cravath client,
before going to General Development.
   Cravath will continue representing the company in three
matters, it said.
