   STATE JUDGE REJECTS ethics charges against a chemical
firm's lawyers.
   Travelers Indemnity Co. of Hartford had alleged that
lawyers for Stauffer Chemical Co. tried to prevent potential
witnesses from testifying in a suit concerning who should pay
for a cleanup of toxic waste.
   The company named in the suit is now a unit of ICI
Americas Inc., of Wilmington, Del., and is called Stauffer
Management Co. A company currently called Stauffer Chemical
Co. is not involved.
   The Travelers Corp. unit, a plaintiff, alleged Stauffer
lawyers violated ethics rules when they sent letters urging
former employees to call Stauffer lawyers at the Wilmington
law firm of Morris, Nichols, Arsht &amp; Tunnell, the Washington
law firm of Kirkpatrick &amp; Lockhart, or the Philadelphia law
firm of Morgan, Lewis &amp; Bockius if they were contacted by the
insurance companies.
   In a ruling last week, Judge Vincent J. Poppiti of
Wilmington wrote that Travelers failed to prove that the
letters prevented the insurer from obtaining information that
would otherwise be available. He said he would refer the
matter to counsel for a lawyers' disciplinary board.
Stauffer's lawyers declined to comment.
   In a separate order, Judge Poppiti wrote that Jeffrey A.
Januzzo and Pamela G. Ostrager, lawyers at the New York firm
of Coudert Brothers, which is representing Travelers, had
misled him about the practices of investigators working on
behalf of the insurer. Stauffer had alleged that the
investigators failed to properly identify themselves to
former employees. The judge terminated the lawyers' right to
appear before the court.
   The Coudert lawyers declined to comment. In a prepared
statement, Mark Lebow, head of Coudert's litigation
department, said, "Two of the most respected ethics experts
in this country, Professor Stephen Gillers of New York
University and Professor Geoffrey Hazard of Yale University,
filed affidavits with the Delaware court attesting that the
conduct of the Coudert Brothers lawyers was ethical." A
Travelers spokesperson said they would appeal.
   Judge Poppiti also ordered Travelers to turn over to
Stauffer any statements obtained from former Stauffer
employees and said they would not be admissible at the trial,
set for February 1991.
